<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-gauss-jordan-elimination" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Gauss-Jordan elimination</title>

<p>
Gauss--Jordan elimination is a method of solving systems of linear equations that is quite similar to 
Gaussian elimination, except it is based on reduced row echelon form instead of REF.
</p>

<definition xml:id="def-RREF">
<statement>
<p>
A matrix is in <term>reduced row echelon form (RREF)</term> if
<ol>
<li>
<p>it is in REF
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>every leading entry is equal to 1
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>all columns that have a leading 1 have zeroes everywhere else.</p>
</li>
</ol></p>
</statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="ex-RREF-matrices">
<statement>
<p>The following two matrices are in RREF.
<me>
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
, \qquad
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  0 \amp  2 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  3 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  1
\end{amatrix}

</me>.
The following three matrices are not in RREF.
<me>
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  2 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  3
\end{amatrix}
, \qquad
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  1\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \amp  2\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  0 \amp  3
\end{amatrix}
, \qquad
\begin{amatrix}{cccc}
  1 \amp  0 \amp  1 \amp  2 \amp  4\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  3 \amp  0 \amp  5\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \amp  -1
\end{amatrix}
</me>.
This is because the first has a leading 3 in its last column, the second is not in REF, and the 
third has a 2 above the leading 1 in the bottom row.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<remark xml:id="rem-RREF">
<p>
The RREF of a matrix is unique! Why?
</p>
</remark>

<definition xml:id="def-GJ-elimination">
<statement>
<p>
<term>Gauss--Jordan elimination</term> is the process of solving a system of linear equations 
by row reducing its augmented matrix to RREF. The solutions can then be read directly from 
the RREF.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
Because every RREF matrix is in REF, Gauss--Jordan is very similar to Gaussian elimination 
at the beginning, but then it has some extra row reduction at the end. Specifically, once 
the matrix is in REF, use each leading entry to make all the entries above it zero. We do 
this starting from the last row and working upwards. This is shown in the next examples.
</p>


<example xml:id="ex-GJ-solving">
<statement>
<p>
Use Gauss--Jordan elimination to solve the following system:
<me>
\begin{cases}
  x + 2y - 3z \amp  = 9 \\
  2x - y + z  \amp  = 0 \\
  4x - y + z  \amp  = 4
\end{cases}
</me>.
Row reducing to RREF gives
<md>
<mrow>
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  2 \amp  -3 \amp  9\\
  2 \amp  -1 \amp  1 \amp  0\\
  4 \amp  -1 \amp  1 \amp  4
\end{amatrix}
\amp\xrightarrow[R_3 \mapsto R_3 - 4R_1]{R_2 \mapsto R_2 -2R_1}           
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  2 \amp  -3 \amp  9\\
  0 \amp  -5 \amp  7 \amp  -18\\
  0 \amp  -9 \amp  13 \amp  -32
\end{amatrix}\\
\amp\xrightarrow{R_2 \mapsto -\frac{1}{5}R_2}
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  2 \amp  -3 \amp  9\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  -\frac{7}{5} \amp  \frac{18}{5}\\
  0 \amp  -9 \amp  13 \amp  -32
\end{amatrix}
\\
\amp\xrightarrow{R_3 \mapsto R_3 + 9R_2}                                  
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  2 \amp  -3 \amp  9\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  -\frac{7}{5} \amp  \frac{18}{5}\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  \frac{2}{5} \amp  \frac{2}{5}\\
\end{amatrix}\\
\amp\xrightarrow{R_3 \mapsto \frac{5}{2}R_3}
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  2 \amp  -3 \amp  9\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  -\frac{7}{5} \amp  \frac{18}{5}\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \amp  1
\end{amatrix}
\\
\amp\xrightarrow[R_2 \mapsto R_2 + \frac{7}{5}R_3]{R_1 \mapsto R_1 + R_3} 
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  2 \amp  0 \amp  12\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  0 \amp  5\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \amp  1
\end{amatrix}\\
\amp\xrightarrow{R_1 \mapsto R_1 - 2R_2}
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  2\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  0 \amp  5\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  1 \amp  1
\end{amatrix}
</mrow>
</md>.
The matrix is now in RREF, and we can read the solution <m>x=2</m>, <m>y = 5</m>, <m>z=1</m>. 
(Notice that the matrix was in REF after the second line of row-reduction. The third line 
shows the steps needed to get it into RREF.)
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<p>
The next example is another example of Gauss--Jordan elimination, as well as an example of 
needing to introduce multiple parameters to solve a system of linear equations.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-multparam">
<statement>
<p>Use Gauss--Jordan elimination to solve the following system of linear equations:
<me>
\begin{cases}
  x + 3y + z + 2w  \amp  = 4  \\
  2x - y + 9z -3w  \amp  = -6 \\
  -x + 2y -6z + 3w \amp  = 6
\end{cases}
</me>.
Row reducing to RREF gives
<md>
<mrow>
\begin{amatrix}{cccc}
  1 \amp  3 \amp  1 \amp  2 \amp  4\\
  2 \amp  -1 \amp  9 \amp  -3 \amp  -6\\
  -1 \amp  2 \amp  -6 \amp  3 \amp  6
\end{amatrix}
\amp\xrightarrow[R_3\mapsto R_3 + R_1]{R_2 \mapsto R_2 - 2R_1}   
\begin{amatrix}{cccc}
  1 \amp  3 \amp  1 \amp  2 \amp  4\\
  0 \amp  -7 \amp  7 \amp  -7 \amp  -14\\
  0 \amp  5 \amp  -5 \amp  5 \amp  10
\end{amatrix}
\\
\amp\xrightarrow{R_2 \mapsto -\frac{1}{7}R_2}                    
\begin{amatrix}{cccc}
  1 \amp  3 \amp  1 \amp  2 \amp  4\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  -1 \amp  1 \amp  2\\
  0 \amp  5 \amp  -5  \amp  5 \amp  10
\end{amatrix}
\\
\amp\xrightarrow[R_3 \mapsto R_3 - 5R_2]{R_1 \mapsto R_1 - 3R_2} 
\begin{amatrix}{cccc}
  1 \amp  0 \amp  4 \amp  -1 \amp  -2\\
  0 \amp  1 \amp  -1 \amp  1 \amp  2\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
</mrow>
</md>
This is in RREF. Let <m>z = s</m> and <m>w = t</m>, for <m>s, t \in \R</m>. (Here we 
are considering the fourth column as the <m>w</m>-column.) Then the solution is
<me>
x = -2 - 4s + t,\; y = 2+s-t,\; z=s,\; w = t, \qquad s, t\in \R.
</me>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<p>
Often Gauss--Jordan elimination is slightly slower than Gaussian elimination. However, it is 
still good to know. Additionally, it introduces the concept of RREF, which will be important 
later for its connection to matrix inverses. 
</p>

</section>